\title{Analyzing Active Directory Acl Abuse}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{active-directory}

\tag{acl-abuse}

\tag{ldap}

\tag{privilege-escalation}

\meta{version}{"1.0"}

\meta{description}{Detect dangerous ACL misconfigurations in Active Directory using ldap3 to identify GenericAll, WriteDACL, and WriteOwner abuse paths}

\subtree{
\title{Analyzing Active Directory ACL Abuse}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Active Directory Access Control Lists (ACLs) define permissions on AD objects through Discretionary Access Control Lists (DACLs) containing Access Control Entries (ACEs). Misconfigured ACEs can grant non-privileged users dangerous permissions such as GenericAll (full control), WriteDACL (modify permissions), WriteOwner (take ownership), and GenericWrite (modify attributes) on sensitive objects like Domain Admins groups, domain controllers, or GPOs.}

\p{This skill uses the ldap3 Python library to connect to a Domain Controller, query objects with their nTSecurityDescriptor attribute, parse the binary security descriptor into SDDL (Security Descriptor Definition Language) format, and identify ACEs that grant dangerous permissions to non-administrative principals. These misconfigurations are the basis for ACL-based attack paths discovered by tools like BloodHound.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{When investigating security incidents that require analyzing active directory acl abuse}
\li{When building detection rules or threat hunting queries for this domain}
\li{When SOC analysts need structured procedures for this analysis type}
\li{When validating security monitoring coverage for related attack techniques}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Python 3.9 or later with ldap3 library (\code{\startverb pip install ldap3\stopverb})}
\li{Domain user credentials with read access to AD objects}
\li{Network connectivity to Domain Controller on port 389 (LDAP) or 636 (LDAPS)}
\li{Understanding of Active Directory security model and SDDL format}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Steps}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Connect to Domain Controller}: Establish an LDAP connection using ldap3 with NTLM or simple authentication. Use LDAPS (port 636) for encrypted connections in production.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Query target objects}: Search the target OU or entire domain for objects including users, groups, computers, and OUs. Request the \code{\startverb nTSecurityDescriptor\stopverb}, \code{\startverb distinguishedName\stopverb}, \code{\startverb objectClass\stopverb}, and \code{\startverb sAMAccountName\stopverb} attributes.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Parse security descriptors}: Convert the binary nTSecurityDescriptor into its SDDL string representation. Parse each ACE in the DACL to extract the trustee SID, access mask, and ACE type (allow/deny).}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Resolve SIDs to principals}: Map security identifiers (SIDs) to human-readable account names using LDAP lookups against the domain. Identify well-known SIDs for built-in groups.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Check for dangerous permissions}: Compare each ACE's access mask against dangerous permission bitmasks: GenericAll (0x10000000), WriteDACL (0x00040000), WriteOwner (0x00080000), GenericWrite (0x40000000), and WriteProperty for specific extended rights.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Filter non-admin trustees}: Exclude expected administrative trustees (Domain Admins, Enterprise Admins, SYSTEM, Administrators) and flag ACEs where non-privileged users or groups hold dangerous permissions.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Map attack paths}: For each finding, document the potential attack chain (e.g., GenericAll on user allows password reset, WriteDACL on group allows adding self to group).}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generate remediation report}: Output a JSON report with all dangerous ACEs, affected objects, non-admin trustees, and recommended remediation steps.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Expected Output}
\pre{\startverb
{
  "domain": "corp.example.com",
  "objects_scanned": 1247,
  "dangerous_aces_found": 8,
  "findings": [
    {
      "severity": "critical",
      "target_object": "CN=Domain Admins,CN=Users,DC=corp,DC=example,DC=com",
      "target_type": "group",
      "trustee": "CORP\\helpdesk-team",
      "permission": "GenericAll",
      "access_mask": "0x10000000",
      "ace_type": "ACCESS_ALLOWED",
      "attack_path": "GenericAll on Domain Admins group allows adding arbitrary members",
      "remediation": "Remove GenericAll ACE for helpdesk-team on Domain Admins"
    }
  ]
}
\stopverb}
}
}